.START 

Investors dumped technology shares and ran for cover to stocks of companies with stable earnings, driving certain sectors of the market sharply higher. 

The Dow Jones Industrial Average rose 21.85 to 2694.91, the largest gain since Aug. 24, when the average broke its all-time record in a 56.53-point rally.
New York Stock Exchange volume rose to 164,240,000 shares, the highest in more than two weeks. 

Despite the rally and the rise in volume, traders said investors didn't trade a broad range of stocks.
Special situations -- technology, airlines, waste management companies and consumer goods -- dominated trading. 

"It's a market that has all kinds of cross-currents," said John B. Burke, a veteran floor trader on the New York Stock Exchange. "The dollar, capital gains, interest rates, technology stocks -- these are the underpinnings of the market.
But the whole thing is awash in conflicting aspects." 

International Business Machines topped the Big Board's most active list, falling 2 1/2 to 109 on nearly four million shares.
Wednesday, the computer giant said profit for the third quarter and the year will be below analysts' expectations. 

IBM's announcement caused a flight to stocks of companies with sound earnings prospects, especially because today is the last trading day of the quarter, and money managers show clients what they own.
Drug stocks gained in the run for big, stable companies.
Merck added 2 1/4 to 76 1/4.
The company announced a marketing and research pact with Du Pont.
Pfizer rose 1 to 68 3/8, and Abbott Labs gained 1 7/8 to 64. 

Consumer stocks also rose in the flight to safety.
Three are in the Dow industrial average: Philip Morris, which gained 4 1/2 to 165; Procter & Gamble, which added 3 1/2 to 120 3/4, and Coca-Cola Co., which climbed 2 7/8 to 67 1/2. 

American Telephone & Telegraph, another Dow stock, climbed 1 1/4 to a 52-week high of 43 7/8 on volume of 1.9 million shares. 

AMR, the owner of American Airlines, soared 4 3/4 to 83 3/4 on 2.1 million shares on various takeover rumors, including talk about a possible joint proposal from AMR's management, American's unions and the Bass family of Texas.
Traders also said there were rumors that Marvin Davis or Donald Trump were buying stock in the company.
Bear Stearns was cited as a heavy buyer of the stock.
AMR declined comment on the rumors. 

Delta Air Lines, which reached a preliminary agreement with Northwest and Trans World airlines for a joint computer reservation system, gained 1 1/8 to 71 3/8.
The Dow Jones Transportation Average rose 10.49 to 1438.12. 

Some brokerage stocks slipped.
Merrill Lynch dropped 1/2 to 30 1/4 as institutional accounts sold the stock in expectation that third-quarter earnings might be disappointing.
Merrill declined to comment on the activity of its stock. 

Elsewhere in the computer sector, Digital Equipment lost 1 3/4 to 91 7/8, Compaq Computer tumbled 1 3/4 to 86 1/2, Hewlett Packard dropped 7/8 to 50 3/8 and Cray Research retreated 1 3/4 to 40 3/4. 

Other tobacco stocks followed the lead of Philip Morris, which said it would launch a new low-smoke cigarette next week.
American Brands jumped 2 to 76 1/2 and UST gained 7/8 to 28. 

As for food and beverage issues, Borden rose 2 1/4 to 36 3/4 after announcing plans for a major restructuring, including the closing or sale of about 25% of its plants and a cutback of about 15% in its work force. 

PepsiCo gained 1 3/8 to 59, Kellogg surged 3 to 73 1/2, General Mills climbed 2 1/8 to 70 1/2 and ConAgra added 1 3/8 to 39. 

Bristol-Myers gained 1 to 52 3/8 in Big Board composite trading of 1.8 million shares.
The Food and Drug Administration approved plans for expanded distribution of DDI, the company's experimental AIDS drug.
Squibb, which plans to merge with Bristol Myers, rose 3 1/8 to 125 3/8. 

Other drug stocks besides Merck to attract buyers included Eli Lilly, which went up 1 3/4 to 62 3/8; Warner-Lambert, up 3 1/4 to 110 1/2; American Home Products, up 1 1/2 to 100 1/2, and Upjohn, up 1/4 to 38 1/4. 

Issues of footwear companies were especially active.
L.A. Gear fell 1 7/8 to 43 1/4 on two million shares as investors took profits after the company reported earnings for the quarter ended in August, which met analysts' estimates.
But its two major competitors both rallied on heavy volume; Reebok International jumped 1 7/8 to 18 1/4 in Big Board dealings, while Nike rose 2 3/8 to 68 in over-the-counter trading. 

Pollution-control stocks, which began to show strength Wednesday, continued to rise as Merrill Lynch, Dean Witter Reynolds and Alex.
Brown & Sons repeated buy recommendations on selected issues. 

Wheelabrator Technologies gained 2 1/2 to 41 3/8, Ogden added 1 1/8 to 33 1/2, Waste Management rose 2 5/8 to 65 3/4 and Browning Ferris Industries went up 1 3/8 to 41 3/8 in Big Board trading.
Chambers Development Class A gained 1 7/8 to 37 5/8 on the American Stock Exchange.
The search for companies with the potential for earnings growth also sent investors to the big-city bank sector, due partly to optimism that Argentina may resume payments on its debt.
Citicorp added 1 1/2 to 34, J.P. Morgan gained 1 1/4 to 44, Chase Manhattan rose 2 3/8 to 43, Chemical Banking advanced 1 1/4 to 39 7/8 and Bankers Trust New York rose 2 to 53 5/8. 

AVX Corp. soared 8 to 29 5/8 as 1.2 million shares changed hands.
Japan's Kyocera agreed to acquire the company in a stock swap valued at about $32 a share. 

Alltel climbed 2 to 38 3/8.
The company said it plans to expand its cellular-telephone operations to cover rural areas in six states; it estimated the expansion would increase the value of those operations by $260 million. 

Phillips Petroleum dropped 7/8 to 25 5/8.
Shearson Lehman Hutton lowered its investment rating on the stock and its earnings estimate for 1989 and 1990, citing deteriorating prices for petrochemicals. 

The American Stock Exchange Index rose 2.71 to 385.75, well above the record high of 384.54 set Sept. 12.
Volume totaled 14,890,000 shares. 

First Iberian Fund fell 1 1/2 to 15 3/8 although most single-country mutual funds moved higher.
On the Big Board, Spain Fund rose 1 1/4 to 31, Austria Fund gained 1 to 15 1/4, Malaysia Fund added 3/4 to 14, Korea Fund advanced 1 7/8 to 41 7/8 and Chile Fund rose 1 1/2 to 18. 

